Scientists have found a way to detect related stars.
Astrophysicists from the University of California at Santa Cruz have studied turbulent mixing and its effect on chemical homogeneity in stellar clusters.
It is expected that the discovery of specialists will allow to search among the stars relatives, that is, the ones that emerged from one cluster.
The results of their research were published by the authors in the journal Nature, and you can find them briefly on the university’s website.
The cause of the same chemical composition of the nearest stars is turbulent mixing in the clouds of gas preceding the formation of the stars.
Even if the star is born then leaves the star cluster, its chemical composition can determine the place of its birth and the region of formation of the stars-relatives.
Previously, scientists had doubts that the evolution of a star outside the cluster could lead to the appearance of differences in its chemical content from that of relatives in the cluster.
The results of the simulation carried out by astrophysicists show that such differences should not appear.
In their study, experts using a supercomputer modeled two interstellar gas streams, which together formed the cloud.
Within a few million years, this object, under the influence of its own gravity, is transformed into a cluster in which protostars begin to form.
The scientists added paint marks to the initial gas flows and found that thanks to the rapid turbulence in the cloud, a high degree of chemical uniformity is achieved.
According to astrophysicists, their study proves that it is possible to search for stars-relatives by chemical composition, as well as to determine possible regions of formation of such objects.
