Remembering the very American ideal that labor rights are human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis proposed a bill in which the organization of trade unions is protected as civil law.
“Where the unions are, there are middle-class jobs,” says Ellison, a Democrat from Minnesota who is co-chair of the Progressive faction Congress.
That is why I am proud to present the Enlargement of Workers' Rights Act along with the symbol of the John Lewis Civil Rights Movement.
This innovative bill will give workers the same legal opportunities when it comes to discrimination against the organization of trade unions as with other forms of discrimination, stopping the forces of the opponents of trade unions.
Amendment of the Labour Relations Regulation Act in such a way as to allow workers who face discrimination for participation in the organization of trade unions to seek justice in civil courts - and to receive compensation for damages and fines - a reasonable and necessary initiative.
However, this is no doubt not a radical initiative – at least according to American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis, and the co-authors of the bill offer is to remember a very American thought.
Despite the attacks of trade unions in recent years—in Wisconsin, Michigan, and other states across the country—the Americans once supported countries around the world in accepting, expanding, and respecting labor rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans still remember when this country at the same time protected democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press and the right to organize.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas McArthur and his aides helped the country adopt a constitution designed to ensure that the militarized autocratic regime of Hideki Tojo was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their trade unions play a role in forming a new Japan, they included a text that explicitly acknowledged that “the right of workers to organize, to negotiate, and to collective action is guaranteed.”
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his aides helped the Germans write a constitution that guaranteed that Adolf Hitler's fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
Acknowledging that workers will need to be organized and heard in the new state, the Germans included an article that openly stated: “The right to form associations in order to protect and improve the working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every person and every profession or sphere of activity.
Agreements that restrict or seek to infringe this right will not have legal force; measures aimed at these purposes will be considered unlawful.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt was president of his own International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which in 1948 would be adopted by the United Nations as a world agreement, Roosevelt and his constituents "involved the guarantee
For generations, Americans have taken the basic position that labor rights are human rights.
When this country consulted other countries on how to create civil and democratic societies, the Americans explained that the right to organize trade unions — and to have this trade union participate as an equal partner in collective negotiations with corporations and government institutions — must be guaranteed.
Now that these rights are under attack in America, it is wise indeed to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to organize and to have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As St. Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the trade union movement did not undermine the strength of the nation, but increased them.
By raising the standard of living of millions, trade unions miraculously created a market for industry and raised the whole nation to an unimaginable level of production.
Those who attack trade unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers how it should be for us.
The official recognition of labour rights as human rights — and the extension of the protection of civil rights to prevent discrimination against the organization of trade unions — has long matured.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis are reviving the ideals that have historically expanded America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
A judge temporarily blocks a law that could shut down all abortion clinics in Louisiana
In the U.S., a federal judge temporarily blocked the passage of Louisiana law on Sunday, which his supporters say is likely to close all five abortion clinics in the state.
According to this measure, which was signed by Louisiana Governor Bobby Ginadal in June and was due to enter into force on September 1, doctors who have abortions would be required to have the authority to receive patients in the hospital within 30 miles of their practice.
However, the judge’s decision means that at the moment doctors can continue to make legal abortions, continuing to seek such powers.
“The plaintiffs will be allowed to work legally, continuing to exercise their powers,” Judge John deGravells wrote in his ruling.
The hearing will be appointed during the month in which the judge will make a more permanent decision under this law.
Defenders of the right to abortion have happily met this decision, the latest in a series of decisions against similar measures, saying that it will give doctors more time to get hospital powers.
“Today’s decision ensures that Louisiana women will be protected from a fraudulent law that seeks to deprive them of their health and rights,” said Nancy Nortap, president and head of the Center for Reproductive Rights, who filed a lawsuit to stop the law from three out of five people.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision would apply to doctors from two clinics who were not plaintiffs in the case and also applied for admission.
Louisiana is one of 11 states that have passed such laws, and courts have recently recognized such measures as unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key parts of the Texas law, which would close most of the remaining clinics in the state, were blocked by a federal judge on Friday.
Abortion advocates, along with the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, say that the laws on the powers of admission impose restrictions on doctors that are not necessary from the point of view of medicine.
Opponents of abortions object that such measures are aimed at protecting women’s health, although some have also noted their positive effect in closing the clinic.
Only one doctor who has an abortion in Louisiana has the authority to be admitted to the hospital, the Center for Reproductive Rights said.
If all other doctors in the state were to be forced to stop performing this procedure, this doctor, fearing for his safety, would stop performing this procedure, the group said.
Criticizing this decision, Louisiana officials said they would not punish doctors who have abortions while their claims to the authority of adoption await the decision.
