Untimely diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment mean that ovarian cancer in rural areas kills more
Angelina Jolie and her brother James released a video of their late mother's memory, who died of ovarian cancer in 2007.
Women who breastfeed in rural Australia face a higher risk of ovarian cancer death than those who live in cities.
The researchers analyzed the disease maps of more than 1,100 Australian women diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 2005, finding that only 35 percent lived five years after the diagnosis was made.
Lead researcher Susan Jordan of the Institute of Medical Research QIMR Berghofer reported that the likelihood of dying during the study is 20 percent higher in those living in regions and remote areas of the state than in those living in urban areas.
LESSONS: New drugs may slow down lung cancer and ovarian cancer <0xE2><0x86><0x92>
The researchers followed the women’s medical path for seven years.
Dr. Jordan said the age of a woman at the time of diagnosis, type of ovarian cancer, the presence of current diseases and socio-economic status also affected the likelihood of survival.
Women of older age, and those who had cancer at a later stage at the time of diagnosis, had the lowest survival rates.
For those who lived in regions or remote areas of the state, the probability of dying during the study was 20 percent higher than for those who lived in urban areas.
Although the study was not intended to determine why women living outside the cities are more likely to die from ovarian cancer, Dr. Jordan suggested that an untimely diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment are possible factors.
“This disease is best treated by surgeons specializing in gynecological oncology, and they are mainly located in large cities,” she said.
Despite improving the quality of telemedicine services to reduce the impact of distance, she suggested that an increase in the number of outbound services that would allow professionals to treat women closer to home, and support programs for people undergoing treatment far from home, could help.
Dr. Jordan said that regardless of the geographic location, the study found that long life expectancy among women with ovarian cancer was rare, stressing the need for more effective treatment and prevention strategies.
The study, funded by Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer Cancer, will be published today in the Medical Journal of Australia.
In March 2012, at the age of 33, a young mother from the Golden Coast, Eli<0xC5><0xA1>e Niv, said she had an aggressive form of ovarian cancer.
