In addition, Wanda owns the American network of AMC Entertainment Holdings cinemas, making the company the largest cinema operator in the world.
By 2015, Wanda plans to equip all of its shopping centers, hotels and entertainment venues with e-commerce services, which will be developed by Alibaba’s once-created competitor.
According to Don Ce, who will lead the new company, thanks to the combination of Wanda will be able to increase the number of users of its e-commerce services from the current 40 million people to 100 million by next year.
The new platform is set to become the world’s largest online-to-offline platform, says Dun Ce.
The essence of online-to-offline (O2O) commerce is to attract buyers on the Internet in order for them to come to regular offline stores or buy other traditional services.
A classic example of O2O is selling coupons like Groupon or Vigoda.ru.
“O2O is the biggest ‘pirog’ in online commerce,” said Wanda Wang Jianglin (Bloomberg quote).
“Now the current O2O site in China does not exist, and in this situation everyone’s chances are approximately equal,” he said.
China’s online market is the largest in the world, and, according to McKinsey & Co., its volume will increase more than three times by 2015 compared to 2011, to $395 billion.
The number of Chinese Internet users has increased to 632 million, according to Bloomberg official statistics: this is more of the population of any country in the world, except India.
And by 2015, that number could grow to 850 million people.
Union of the Rich
Tencent's head Ma Huateng until recently was China's richest man, however, according to Bloomberg's millionaires index, Alibaba founder Jack Ma has already rounded it up to $5.5 billion.
Jack Ma’s fortune is estimated at $21.8 billion, of which $11 billion comes to his share in Alibaba.
Baidu leader Robin Lee is now ranked third among China’s richest people, while Wanda’s Van Jianglin is ranked fourth in the ranking.
