MPs proposed to speed up the entry into force of the Personal Data Act
In case of success of the initiative, the data of Russians will not be stored on servers abroad from 1 January 2015
The State Duma introduced a draft law providing for the transfer of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law on personal data of Russians - from September 1, 2016 to January 1, 2015.
The initiative is placed in the basis of legislative activity of the lower house.
Its authors were the deputies of the State Duma Vadim Dengin, Yaroslav Nilov (LDPR), Evgeny Fedorov ("United Russia"), Vladimir Parachin ("Justice Russia") and Alexander Yushchenko (KPRF).
Such a change, according to the authors of the initiative, will contribute to a more efficient and effective guarantee of the rights of the citizens of the Russian Federation to the preservation of personal data and compliance with the secrecy of correspondence in information and telecommunications networks.
The law, the entry into force of which is hastened by parliamentarians, obliges to store in the territory of the Russian Federation personal data of Russians processed via the Internet.
It also makes mandatory the recording, systematization, storage, storage, clarification and extraction of personal data of Russian citizens, in databases located on the territory of Russia, as well as the indication of the location of such databases.
In addition, the law gives Roskomnadzor the right on the basis of the court’s decision to restrict access to information processed in violation of the legislation of the Russian Federation in the field of personal data.
The law also proposes the creation of so-called “blacklists” of infringers’ websites – an automated information system “The Register of Violators of the Rights of Personal Data Subjects”.
This law was passed by the State Duma in the summer.
The authors of the bill were Andrei Lugovoi and Vadim Dengin from LDPR and Alexander Yushchenko from KPRF.
Dengin and Yushchenko are also among the authors of the current bill on the transfer of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law.
Those who do not have data centers in Russia will have to pay for the rent
Commenting on the draft law submitted to the State Duma today, Leonid Levin, the first deputy head of the Duma Information Policy Committee, said he did not see any problems with the transfer of the date of entry into force of the Personal Data Protection Act.
According to him, those companies that by January 1, 2015 will not have their own storage of Russian personal data on the territory of the Russian Federation will be able to rent them, for example, in "Rostelekoma", which repeatedly said that they are ready to provide their servers for rent, the Group will be able to rent out the company, and will be able to sell them.
“In addition, there are several independent data centers that are ready to cooperate in this area,” he added.
"If companies decide to comply with the law and continue to work in the territory of the Russian Federation, I see no problems - they will get technological opportunities for placement," Levin said.
Controversial bill
Immediately after the publication of the draft law, the Russian Association of Electronic Communications feared that in the event of the adoption of the bill, Russians would no longer be able to use many global Internet services.
In particular, it is about the services of online booking of airline tickets and hotels.
