The fact is that the savings certificates for the depositors do not fall into the deposit insurance system, and they are cheaper to the bank, as there is no need to make deductions to the Fund of the Deposit Insurance Agency (ASA).
The pique of the situation is that this step is planned to be taken because of small and medium-sized banks that distribute such certificates, and are affected by it by Sberbank and the Bank of Moscow, which, according to ASV estimates, control 98% of the profile market.
And the share of the Bank of Moscow, according to the estimates of the agency, is about 3.5%.
The problem, explained in the ASV, is that customers of a small bank who bought such a certificate, in case of revocation of his licenses try to get money in the ASV.
Some depositors, who do not have sufficient financial literacy and who purchase savings certificates on the depositor, may assume that their investments are insured.
A well-founded lack of insurance payments on these certificates in case of revocation of a license from a bank can lead to misunderstanding and social tension.
In practice, there have been cases where the holders of the presentation certificates tried to recover insurance compensation through the court”, – stated in the ASV.
The problem, of course, is thoughtful.
After all, no one will pay the buyers of the certificates anyway, because they are legally not entitled to compensation from the state.
If it were to be that the instrument is not insured in the ASV, it would be prohibited along with it the metal accounts, on which the funds of citizens are counted in grams of one of the four metals - gold, silver, platinum and palladium.
After all, these accounts also do not fall into the deposit insurance system, but for their existence no one is trying.
The thing, most likely, is that the certificates on the presenter are very convenient securities, which can actually act as quasi-money.
At the same time, their movement is virtually out of control: any customer of the bank can buy a certificate, hand over it to any citizen, and before the receipt of such certificate can change many owners.
It is not by chance that the bill stipulates that a savings certificate must be a security that must be kept in the depositary.
