The SCRC has stopped the investigation of the Tu-204 disaster in Vnukovo
The Investigative Committee of Russia (SCR) has suspended the criminal case on the fact of the crash of the Tu-204 aircraft of the Red Wings airline.
This is reported by the press service of the department.
The decision was made in connection with the death of the commander of the aircraft and the flight engineer.
The forensic examination showed that the cause of the disaster was the increased speed of take-off, failure by the crew of the standard procedures on landing, as well as the unintended exit of the engines for increased direct-tension turns.
The Tu-204 aircraft of the Red Wings, which followed the flight from Prague to Moscow, suffered a crash on December 29, 2012 when landing at Moscow’s Vnukovo airport.
The airship went out behind the runway and burned down.
At the scene of the accident, the commander of the aircraft, the second pilot and a flight engineer were killed.
Two onboard conductors were taken to medical facilities, where they subsequently died from the injuries received.
Three other onboard conductors, hospitalized with severe bodily injury, underwent long-term treatment.
In addition, serious bodily damage was received by the driver of the car, which was moving at the time of the accident on the Kiev highway.
There were no passengers on board the aircraft.
The transport prosecutor's office after the crash conducted a check at the Red Wings, during which numerous violations were identified.
In February 2013, the airline’s license was suspended.
The company resumed operations in the summer of 2013.
