Anger was the most universal and functional emotion of man.
A person’s harsh expression is biologically universal to humanity, and every person involved in its creation is not a random organ and muscle group, but is an additional means of expressing power and threat, Australian and U.S. scientists have found.
They told about their discoveries in the journal Evolution and Human Behavior, and briefly about them can be read in the press release of the University of California, Santa Barbara.
The angry expression of the face - moved and lowered down the eyebrows, stretched into a thin line of lips, swollen nostrils - is the same in all cultures, and makes it even blind from the birth of children, who have never seen it, notes the lead author of the study Aaron.
As part of a major research project dedicated to the nature of anger, the researchers found that this emotion was created for the effective conduct of disputes during the conflict.
The more physical damage one person can inflict on another, the more he has the ability to dictate his conditions, and he brings it to the interlocutor by means of anger.
The researchers found evidence and another of their hypotheses: physically strong people are more likely to get angry and switch to handcuffs, consider themselves entitled to impose conditions on others that are not beneficial to them, and prefer force-based methods of resolving conflicts peacefully.
Relying on the fact that anger is first and foremost an “emotion of bargaining”, the scientists decided that the movements of each of the seven groups of muscles that create the angry expression of the face should represent the angry individual more powerful and dangerous in the eyes of the interlocutor – and thus force him to concur with his condition as possible.
To test this hypothesis, the researchers modeled on the computer of the face, where each of the seven elements of the angry face was present or absent, and showed them to the informants.
Although abandoned eyebrows or protruded eyebrows did not make the face evil in isolation, the person depicted with such traits as the stronger physical participants of the study admitted unanimously.
Man’s anger, like animals, expresses a threat: an exaggerated manifestation of one’s own strength, forcing one to agree and obey.
A man shakes his nostrils and presses his lips with the same purpose as a spoon that is soaked, or a granny that shows off his claws.
Anger "starts" by the refusal of the interlocutor to accept the situation, and the person immediately takes the form, as effectively as possible demonstrating the opposite side of the consequences of this refusal.
But the most striking thing is that none of the components of the angry face is arbitrary, they all express the same thing,” said anthropologist John Tubby.
The Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate 250 million rubles of the TV company "Crimea"
In 2014, the Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate 250 million rubles from the federal budget of the autonomous non-profit organization "Teleradio Company "Crime".
This is stated in the draft resolution of the Government prepared by the Ministry, which was introduced by "Lenta.ru".
According to the explanatory note to the project, subsidies from the federal budget will be directed "to cover the costs of creating the conditions for large-scale informational coverage of the socio-economic situation and development of the modern information space on the territory of the Republic of Crimea".
In particular, the money allocated is supposed to be converted into a hardware-studio block, a video wall, a central hardware and a video server.
It is also planned to purchase a mobile TV station and satellite transmitter.
In addition, from the allocated funds, the company will pay for the use of fiber-optic communication line (VOLS) and the repair of the energy system.
Subsidies will be provided within the limits of the federal budget provided for the Ministry of Communications.
The state television broadcasting company "Crimea" was established in 1959, broadcasting in seven languages: Ukrainian, Russian, Crimean Tatar, German, Greek, Bulgarian and Armenian.
To date, the coverage of the television signal of the television company is more than 75 percent of the territory of the peninsula.
In 2011, the TV company "Crime" received a license for television broadcasting in digital format.
